<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-048-972  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 048 972.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  Dec 1989 v29 n12 p15(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The software design document: more than a user's manual.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bowers, Dennis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A software design document is as valuable as, or even morevaluable than, the software itself.andP;  A design document shouldinclude a description of the purpose of the software, a productionplan, pseudocode overview of the program's operation, a flowchart,a narrative description of the program logic and main routines orfunctions, graphic representation of screen displays, adescription of testing, copies of the documentation accompanyingthe finished product, and listings of the program code.andP;  Reportingdiffers for different programming environments.andP;  Apple Computer'sHyperCard and HyperTalk is an example of an environment requiringspecific, unique reporting in the design document.andP;  The designdocument is important not only to other programmers but also topublishers and university tenure committees.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Hypercard (Data base management system) (usage).andO;Topic:     Software DesignDocumentationHypertextTutorialEducational Software.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   Sample pseudocode. (table)Flowchart for a simple instructional program. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>